column42: Locally abundant. More or less erect herb to 30 cm, with well developed tap root. Flowers pinkish, bracts whitish with some pink on reverse, flowering stems sprawling but erect at the ends.
column57: Flattish area on ridge with rock platforms covered in heath of Leptospermum & Calytrix with Callitris in deeper soil pockets. Area burnt winter 1991. Sandy soil on sandstone.
column75: On no. 7 fire trail to Wolgan Pinnacle, 4.6 km north of Sunnyside Road, ›Newnes Plateau,  Newnes State Forest.
column76: On no. 7 fire trail to Wolgan Pinnacle, 4.6 km north of Sunnyside Road, ›Newnes Plateau.

column42: Locally dominant ground cover, forming large patches between burnt blackened veg. Spreading herb, radiating from central point, upto 1 m diameter x 35 cm high. VOUCHER for image.
column57: Exposed sandstone plateau, narrow ridge adjacent to crest. Tall heath, 1 year post fire, of Banksia ericifolia, Hakea dactyloides, Eucalyptus stricta, Leptospermum trinervium, L. polygalifolium, Xanthorrhoea, with heavy regrowth of grasses and herbs, sedges 1 year post fire. Very little recruitment of Banksia or Hakea observed post fire. Roadside weeds of Eragrostis curvula, Oenothera glazioviana abundant.
column75: c. 1.4 km WSW along Glenraphael Drive / Narrow Neck Plateau Trail from Cliff Drive, Katoomba, Blue Mountains National Park.

column42: Plants prostrate/creeping to 10 cm high. Inflorescence bracts white with pink underside, in 2 whorls, outer whorl darker pink, inner whorl held above. Male and female phases overlapping (different inflorescences on the same individual).
column57: Burnt Allocasuarina - Banksia heath with Lambertia, Xanthorrhoea, Hakea, Petrophile, Leptospermum and sedges. Evidence (dead plants) of having been very common following fire. Live plants scarce. Sandstone.
